sentence-detokenized: The EU rejects Germany's call for a boycott of British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRISELE 1996-08-22

The European Commission said on Thursday that it does not agree with Germany's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb until scientists determine whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Werner Zwingmann, Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheepmeat from countries other than the UK until scientific advice is clearer.
"We do not support this recommendation because we see no justification for it," said Commission spokesman Nicolaus van der Pass at a press briefing.
He said that further scientific research was needed and that if action was found to be necessary, it should be carried out by the EU.

He said that the proposal made last month by EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler to ban sheep marrow, spleen and spinal cord from the human and animal food chain is a very specific and precautionary measure to protect human health.
Mr Fischler proposed EU-wide measures following reports in the UK and France that sheep can contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - mad cow disease - in laboratory conditions.

But Fischler agreed to reconsider his proposal after the EU's Standing Veterinary Committee, an international animal health official, questioned whether such action was justified because there was only a small risk to human health.
Earlier, Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio accused Fischer of unjustified alarmism by "dangerous generalisations" at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers.
Only France and the UK supported the proposal.
Early next month, the EU's scientific veterinary and interdisciplinary committees will re-examine the issue and make recommendations to senior veterinary officials.
It has long been known that sheep can contract scrapie, a brain-damaging disease similar to BSE, which is thought to have been transmitted to cattle through feed containing animal waste.

British farmers on Thursday denied that their sheep pose a risk to human health, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could affect consumers across Europe.
"We need to be very careful about how other countries take up the German example," John Lloyd Jones, President of the National Farmers Union of Wales (NFU), told BBC Radio.

Bonn has led efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence plummeted in March following the publication of a report in the UK suggesting that people eating contaminated beef could contract a disease similar to mad cow disease.
Last year, Germany imported 47 600 sheep from the UK, almost half of the total.
It imported 4,275 tonnes of British mutton, representing around 10% of total imports.
Rare Hendrix song drafts sell for almost USD 17 000.
A rare early handwritten draft version of a song by US guitar legend Jimi Hendrix was sold for nearly 17 000 USD at the musician's favourites auction on Thursday.
A restaurant in Florida paid £10 925 ($16 935) for a draft of "Ain't no telling", which Hendrix wrote on London hotel stationery in late 1966.
At the end of a concert in Nottingham, England, in January 1967, he threw a piece of paper into the audience, where it was retrieved by a fan.
The buyers also bought 16 other items offered at auction by Hendrix's ex-girlfriend Kathy Etchingham, who lived with Hendrix from 1966 to 1969.
Among them was a black lacquer and mother-of-pearl inlaid box used by Hendrix to store the drugs, which was purchased by an anonymous Australian buyer for £5060 ($7845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970 at the age of 27.
China says Taiwan is spoiling the atmosphere for talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China on Thursday accused Taipei of spoiling the atmosphere for the resumption of cross-Strait talks when Taiwanese Vice President Lien Chan visited Ukraine this week, a move that angered Beijing.

Just hours after Chinese state media announced that the time had come to start political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Sheng Guofang told Reuters: 'The Taiwanese authorities have obstructed the atmosphere necessary for the talks to begin. "The Taiwanese authorities have obstructed the opening of talks.
State media quoted China's chief negotiator with Taipei, Tang Shubei, as telling a Taiwan visiting team on Wednesday that the time had come for the rivals to start political talks.
"Now is the time for both sides to engage in political negotiations...
is to end the hostility," Thursday's People's Daily quoted Tan as saying.

Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen said in an interview with Reuters television that he had read reports about Tang's comments, but gave no details on why the negotiator believed the time was right for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers an apostate province.
China, which has long opposed all of Taipei's efforts to gain more international recognition, was angered by Taiwanese Vice President Lien's visit to Ukraine this week.
China says it's time to talk about Taiwan.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China has declared that the time has come for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island must take practical steps to achieve this goal.

Consultations should be held to determine the timing and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency quoted Tang Shubei, executive vice-chairman of the Association for Cross-Strait Relations, as saying late on Wednesday evening.
In Germany, the number of cars registered in July rose by 14.2 percentage points year-on-year.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
The number of vehicles registered for the first time in Germany increased by 14.2% in July this year compared to the previous year, the Federal Motor Vehicle Office said on Thursday.
The Bureau reported that 356 725 new cars were registered in July 1996 - 304 850 cars and 15 613 trucks.
Compared to July 1995, these figures are 13.6% higher for passenger cars and 2.2% lower for trucks.
Motorcycle registrations increased by 32.7% over the same period.
The increase was partly due to an increase in the number of Germans buying German cars abroad, but manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal office said.
Almost all German carmakers registered higher car registrations during the period.
Volkswagen AG obtained 77,719 registrations, just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG and General Motors were in second place with 49,269 registrations, 16.4% of the total.
Ford came third with 35 563 registrations, or 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche registered fewer cars in July 1996 than in July last year.
Seat registered 3,420 cars, compared to 5,522 in July a year ago.
The number of Porsche registrations fell from 643 to 554.

Israel downplays concerns about war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUZALEME 1996-08-22
On Thursday, Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said the current tensions between the two countries seemed like a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israel's ambassador in Washington led fruitless talks with Syria, told Israel Radio that it looks like Damascus wants to talk, not fight.
"It seems to me that {(1)[MISC] Syria's priority} is still negotiations.
The Syrians are confused, they are certainly tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is basically a storm in a teacup," he said.
Rabinovic ceases to be Ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, former Israeli envoy to Egypt and politician from the right-wing Likud party.
Israel sent a message to Syria on Wednesday, via Washington, expressing its commitment to peace and its willingness to start negotiations without preconditions.
But it rebuked Damascus for creating what it considered a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria on Wednesday accused Israel of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently tested a missile.
It claimed that the arms purchases were made for defence purposes.

"The message we sent (to Syrian President Hafez al-Assad) is that Israel is ready to start peace talks at any time without preconditions," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levi said in an interview with Israel Radio.
Since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June promising to preserve the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war, tensions have risen.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks on the Golan have been deadlocked since 1991, even though the previous government was ready to make concessions on the Golan.
Peace talks between the two sides last took place in February.
"The voices coming out of Damascus are bad, not good.
Media...
is full of expressions and statements that are worrying...
this artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who spread it can become its prisoners," said Levy.
"We expect Syria to respond to Israel's call for peace talks if they are aimed at peace, because that is our goal," he said. "
We do not want war, God forbid.
No one benefits from wars. "
Israel's Channel 2 television said that Damascus had sent a "reassuring signal" to Israel.
The report does not indicate the source.
Spokespersons for Netanyahu and Levy said they could not confirm this.
The television also pointed out that Netanyahu has sent messages to reassure Syria through Cairo, the US and Moscow.
A Polish diplomat denies that nurses are trapped in Libya.

A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied reports published by a Polish tabloid this week that Libya had refused exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"That's not true.

So far, we have no reports of any nurse being trapped or held in Libya without her will and we have not received any complaints," Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, Charge d'Affaires at the Polish Embassy in Tripoli, told Reuters by phone.

The Polish Labour Ministry said this week it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Mr Awdankiewicz said the investigation was prompted by complaints from some nurses about working conditions, such as non-payment of wages.
He said there are about 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafid
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
An Iraq-based Iranian exile group on Thursday pledged support to Iranian Kurdish rebels after Iraqi troops attacked them deep inside Iraq last month.

The Mujahideen Khalq said in a statement that its leader, Massoud Rajavi, met the Secretary General of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI), Hassan Rastegar, in Baghdad on Wednesday and expressed support for the Kurdish rebels in Iran.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian resistance will continue to stand shoulder to shoulder with its Kurdish compatriots and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan," the statement said.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "signals a new level of cooperation between the Mujahideen Khalq and the Iranian Kurdish opposition".
In July, Iran intensively bombed targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of KDPI guerrillas based in Kurdish areas of Iraq not controlled by the government in Baghdad.
The Kurdish areas of Iraq bordering Iran are controlled by guerrillas from the Patriotic Union of Iraqi Kurdistan (PUK).
The PUK and the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), the two main Iraqi Kurdish factions, have controlled northern Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War, when Iraqi forces were forced out of Kuwait.
Over the weekend, the two sides clashed in their most serious clashes since the US-sponsored ceasefire last year.
Mujahideen Khalq stated that Iranian troops had also shelled KDP positions in the Kasri region of Suleimaniya province near the Iranian border in the last two days.
It said that around 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or wounded in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey are carrying out air and ground strikes against targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their Kurdish insurgents.
US-led air forces in southern Turkey protect Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad forces.
Saudi riyals rates are stable in quiet summer trade.
The Saudi spot market against the dollar and the level of interbank deposit rates were mostly stable in quiet summer trading this week, dealers in the Kingdom said.
"Saudi Riyals rates remained unchanged.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," said one trader.
The spot rate of the Riyal was 3.7504/06 per dollar.
One-month interbank deposits were 5-1/2, 3/8%, three-month 5-5/8, 1/2% and six-month 5-3/4, 5/8%.
The amount of one year's funds was six, 5-7/8 percent.
Israel confirms Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUZALEME 1996-08-22

Israel on Thursday gave Palestinian President Yasser Arafat permission to fly over its territory to the West Bank, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the Palestinian Authority, an Arafat adviser said.
"The problem is solved.
The President's plane has been cleared to cross Israeli airspace, but the President is not expected to travel to the West Bank before Monday," Nabil Abu Rdainah told Reuters.

Arafat was due to meet former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Thursday, but after Israel refused to allow the Palestinian leader's helicopters to fly, the meeting venue was changed to Gaza.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to stop the Ramallah meeting by preventing Arafat from reaching the ground.
Arafat then cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials on civilian issues at the Allenby Bridge crossing Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu Rdainah said that Arafat had decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, when Israel lifted the ban, because he had a tight schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.
Arafat will meet Peres in Gaza after the flight ban.
JERUZALEME 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday after the Palestinians announced that Israel's right-wing government had prevented the Palestinian leader from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
